attribs.name: mask
attribs.current:
Yusef Shamsin is an assumed name, inserted into the proper databases and with the appropriate records, although all created from whole cloth rather than stolen from some dead or living person to avoid getting outed by an in-depth investigation into his personage. 

Young, single, college aged graduate with a degree in Architectural Engineering.

attribs.name: mortal_history
attribs.current:
His parents were first generation immigrants and he was one of 4 other children, 3 sisters and a brother, and while this did create what he saw at the time as an awful living environment full of strife and expectations, looking back at it he still smiles and enjoys telling stories, or at least he thinks he would if anyone were to ever ask. Schooling for him was involved, something he was always working hard in and involving himself in everything that he could, although he did end up dropping out of wrestling much to his father and brothers chagrin. Being a rather small child who bloomed later in life he simply wasn't cut out for it. He wasn't one who could handle failure well. 

In truth he threw himself into schooling and extracurricular because he felt lost. He didn't know what he was doing or what he wanted, and as time went on this built into a general ennui. He started growing distant from his friends and family, never cutting contact properly but focusing on other things. He started taking time out of his day, whenever he didn't have some other mandatory obligation to travel around his small home town, trying to see if anything would spark that inspiration. He found it in witnessing the first of Wayne Boden's murders. And so his fascination and voyeurism began. An obsession even, that he began to follow up on wherever he could. Reading, writing, building his life around it. When computers and gaming became probable, consumer grade products, his fantasies were able to expand beyond simple writing and drawing. 

Obsessed with criminal psychology, especially serial killers, he ...

attribs.current: A Blood Doll. I'm sort of imagining them as similar to Klaus Hargreeves, at least in personality because I quite liked him. Nothing particularly exciting here, just a sad addicted person.

attribs.name: repeating_beliefs_-LWi6n9Xsqq7rXCHc9o0_touchstone_details
attribs.current: Criminal Psychologist: (Part of the Toronto PD) She continued her education in the Department of Psychology in Istanbul University. She was educated in Sinop Municipal Conservatory before transferring to Yale, finishing her degree with a profitable job offer waiting for her. She has, more or less, had the biggest negative impact on Yusef's life that he can recall, putting him through the mental health system, dosing him with medication, and effectively contributing to the eventual destruction of his social life, school life, and work life. Although she'd tell you it was all for a good cause, Yusef struggles to relate to this. Major issues reap major consequences, although minor ones earn sympathy and help.

attribs.name: repeating_beliefs_-LWi7FPJ81PYyj5thrEO_touchstone_details
attribs.current: A strange man who's half mad, he "heads" more than a few homeless communities in the city where those without kith and kin can find a night of shelter and food. It's not a great system for all involved, and he is shamelessly exploitative of those under his care, but with connections both criminal and mundane, you'll be hard pressed to find a better benefactor. A bit of a duality of character, he's ruthless and caring, and which side you see depends on who's side you're on. Loyalty is rewarded.

attribs.name: repeating_others_-LWiCCo-VqOJlX3S-yUU_kr_otherdetails
attribs.current:
In addition to the three Nosferatu you created, there are four more Camarilla Nosferatu that you are aware of (and you have no reason to believe Clan Nosferatu would hide the existence of a fifth). In order of age, starting with the youngest:

- Ian Rammond:  A recent arrival to the city, this 13th-generation neonate is a young and timid mouse amidst a sea of hungry predators.  The rest of the city's Nosferatu have done all they can to protect and guide the young vampire, but some are starting to say he may not have handled his transformation... well. He refuses to discuss why he left his former city, a point of concern but also irritation among the secret-loving Nosferatu.
- Emily, the Dusk Rose:  A 10th-generation ancilla, Emily is the real scourge: she arranged for Raphael Bishop to pose as scourge to deflect attention from her so she could work in secret.  In exchange, she's helping Bishop escape the leash of his sire, Seneschal Scheer. Despite working against Scheer, she is a zealous defender of the Third Tradition and she will readily destroy any vampire confirmed to have been Embraced outside the law.
- The Aristocrat:  An ancilla at the top of Nosferatu status games in the city; he'd be primogen, you've heard, had the prince not disbanded the council once the Beckoning had claimed most of its elders.  The "Aristocrat" moniker started as a slur used to mock his presence in Elysium, wearing tailored suits and expensive colognes as if they could distract from his gaunt features, shark-like eyes, and the aroma of fish that hangs off him.  But, in true Nosferatu fashion, he embraced the name and wears it as a badge of pride.
- Drake:  Drake is a 7th-generation Nosferatu elder of at least six centuries, putting him on par with the city's two autarkes (and a step or two above Scheer).  Unfortunately, he and Scheer are allies --- they both share the conviction that Toronto is and always will be a Camarilla city.  It was Drake who suggested Scheer reach out to the Piece-Taker following the admission of the Banu Haqim into the Camarilla (Scheer, ever the coward, "delegated" the task to his childe, Raphael Bishop, who you know from your Detection Project has been doing just that).

You also know of a Nosferatu Antitribu in the city:

- Sang-Froid:  A French Canadian with a penchant for eating frozen blood, he spends most summers in voluntary torpor and emerges in the winter to terrorize homeless people sleeping in the cold, chasing them from their warm spots over subway grates and harrying them through the city until they die of hypothermia.  He's a rather unpleasant conversationalist, too.

And then there are a few things you know through the Nosferatu rumor-mill:

- Sheriff Laz --- Laz is in trouble.  He's gone too far in his overtures to the Anarchs for aid, and wheels are in motion to replace him.  The Nosferatu in general are very much opposed to this, not only because Laz is one of them, but also because he's the only one who seems to give a damn about actually solving the problems in Toronto.  They have reasonably high opinions of the baroness, and approve of the two of them exploring the possibility of working together.
- The Peerage -- The Nosferatu know exactly what it is, and so do you:  It's a group of elders comprising former primogen under Prince Steeles rule, who went into hiding after the Beckoning halved their number and the prince disbanded the council.  Drake is a member of the Peerage, as are at least two others, although thus far Drake has honored his oath to keep their identities secret even from his kin.
- The Island Devil --- The Island Devil is an enigma to any Nosferatu willing to talk about him.  Most seem to think he's on the verge of losing it entirely and becoming a wight (which, given his age and skillset, would spell disaster for Toronto).  Others point to his curious inclination to shelter Sabbat as evidence that there's more meaning to his madness than appearances suggest.
- The Sabbat --- Speaking of Sabbat:  They're currently in a holding pattern.  Up until recently, all of them were contained on Centre Island.  But at least one Lasombra ancilla has managed to infiltrate the city without passing through any of the monitored channels.  The Nosferatu have concluded he received help, but they have no leads as to who.  Regardless, their numbers remain too small to launch any kind of coordinated offensive, with Sang-Froid's count being five, including himself, last he checked.

attribs.name: repeating_advantage_-LcONQyuzFtThX38RTce_advantage_details
attribs.current:
Security 2: our haven has a better-than-average security system. For each dot of this Merit, add one die to your dice pool to resist (or alert you to) unauthorized entry into your haven. 

Postern 1: Your Haven has a rear exit, secret tunnel, grating in the cellar leading into the sewers, or other unobtrusive way out. For each dot of this Merit, add one die to your dice pools to evade or escape surveillance near your haven.

Location 1: Your haven nestles in one of the most fashionable or otherwise exclusive areas of the city, in the Rack, on a small island, or otherwise in a prime spot. Add two dice (or +2 to foes’ Difficulty) to bonuses on the relevant die rolls from either Chasse (p. 195) or from your base Haven rating (pick one). If neither modifier precisely maps to what you have in mind, work out with your Storyteller when you can expect a two-dice bonus to occur. For example, a Haven close to Elysium might grant a two-dice bonus to Etiquette tests in Elysium and on tests to pick up on court gossip.
(Provides +2 to foes difficulty to locate or enter the Haven)

Luxury 1:High-definition flat screens, designer furniture, objets d’art, or other expensive details give you a two-dice bonus to Social tests dealing with mortal guests in your haven. If you don’t have at
least three dots of Resources (•••), your décor was gained illegally

attribs.current:
Your Mask can pass a background check with the national police: FBI, Scotland Yard, or the equivalent. If you had a military or intelligence record in life, it has been classified.

Cobbler: You can make or source Masks. Making a Mask takes three days per dot and possibly exposes you online; sourcing Masks
takes one day per dot, but costs something in return. How much depends on your leverage, margin on the Social test, or whatever else
the Storyteller decides.
